mir Ordain |publisher=MLSsoccer.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/players/jhamir-kareem-ordain-alexander/128783/|title=Costa Rica - J. Ordian - Profile with news, career statistics and history - Soccerway|website=us.soccerway.com}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOrdain made his [[Costa Rica national football team]] debut in the [[2017 Copa Centroamericana]] playing in 3-0 win over [[Belize national football team|Belize]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.com/m/528036/2017-01-15/copa-centroamericana/belize/costa-rica|title=Belize vs Costa Rica 0 - 3 - Copa Centroamericana - 2017 Panama - Final Round - World Football|website=www.worldfootball.com}}</ref> He also played in a 0-0 draw against [[Nicaragua national football team|Nicaragua]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stumptownfooty.com/platform/amp/2017/1/25/14385262/are-the-portland-timbers-pursuing-jhamir-ordain|title=Are the Portland Timbers Pursuing Jhamir Ordain? Update: Maybe?|website=www.stumptownfooty.com}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Costa Rica squad 2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ordain, Jhamir}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican footballers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n\n\n{{CostaRica-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Costa Rican footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Costa Rican footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jhamir_Ordain"}
{"title_page": "Giuseppe Arcimboldo", "text_new": "{{short description|16th-century Italian painter of the late Renaissance}}\n{{redirect|Arcimboldi|the cardinal|Giovanni Arcimboldi}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #EEDD82\n| name          = Giuseppe Arcimboldo\n| image         = Giuseppe Arcimboldo - Self Portrait - Google Art Project.jpg\n| imagesize     = 150px\n| caption       = ''Self-portrait'', now in [[National Gallery in Prague]], [[Google Art Project]]\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 1527 \n| birth_place   = [[Milan]], [[Duchy of Milan]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date|1593|7|11|df=y}} (aged 66\u201367)\n| death_place   = Milan, [[Duchy of Milan]]\n| nationality   = [[Italians|Italian]]\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      =\n| works         = ''[[The Librarian (painting)|The Librarian]]'', 1566<br>\n''[[Vertumnus (painting)|Vertumnus]]'', 1590\u20131591<br>\n''Flora'', ca. 1591\n| patrons       =\n| awards        =\n}}\n'''Giuseppe Arcimboldo''' ({{IPA-it|d\u0292u\u02c8z\u025bppe art\u0283im\u02c8b\u0254ldo|lang}}; also spelled ''Arcimboldi'') (1526 or 1527 \u2013 11 July 1593) was an [[List of Italian painters|Italian painter]] best known for creating imaginative portrait [[human head|head]]s made entirely of objects such as fruits, vegetables, flowers, fish and books.\n\nThese works form a distinct category from his other productions. He was a conventional [[court painter]] of portraits for three [[Holy Roman Emperor]]s in Vienna and Prague, also producing religious subjects and, among other things, a series of coloured drawings of exotic animals in the imperial [[menagerie]]. He specialized in grotesque symbolical compositions of fruits, animals, landscapes, or various inanimate objects arranged into human forms.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Oxford illustrated encyclopedia|date=1985-1993|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Judge, Harry George., Toyne, Anthony.|isbn=0-19-869129-7|location=Oxford [England]|pages=21|oclc=11814265}}</ref> The [[still-life]] portraits were clearly partly intended as whimsical curiosities to amuse the court, but critics have speculated as the degree of serious engagement with [[Renaissance Neo-Platonism]] or other intellectual currents that they have. \n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Vertumnus \u00e5rstidernas gud m\u00e5lad av Giuseppe Arcimboldo 1591 - Skoklosters slott - 91503.tiff|thumb|''[[Vertumnus (painting)|Vertumnus]]'', a portrait depicting [[Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor]] painted as [[Vertumnus]], the Roman God of the seasons, c. 1590\u20131. [[Skokloster Castle]], Sweden.]]\n[[File:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - Four Seasons in One Head - Google Art Project.jpg|thumbnail|''Four Seasons in One Head'', [[National Gallery of Art]], USA. ]]\nGiuseppe's father, Biagio Arcimboldo, was an artist of [[Milan]]. Like his father, Giuseppe Arcimboldo started his career as a designer for stained glass and frescoes at local cathedrals when he was 21 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giuseppe-arcimboldo.org/biography.html |title=Giuseppe Arcimboldo Biography |publisher=Giuseppe-arcimboldo.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref> \n\nIn 1562, he became court portraitist to [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] at the [[Habsburg]] court in [[Vienna]], Austria and later, to [[Maximilian II, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian II]] and his son [[Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor|Rudolf II]] at the court in [[Prague]]. He was also the court decorator and costume designer. [[Augustus, Elector of Saxony]], who visited [[Vienna]] in 1570 and 1573, saw Arcimboldo's work and commissioned a copy of his ''The Four Seasons'' which incorporates his own monarchic [[symbol]]s.\n\nArcimboldo's conventional work, on traditional religious subjects, has fallen into oblivion, but his portraits of human heads made up of vegetables, plants, fruits, sea creatures and tree roots, were greatly admired by his contemporaries and remain a source of fascination today.\n\nAt a distance, his portraits looked like normal human portraits.  However, individual objects in each portrait were actually overlapped together to make various anatomical shapes of a human.  They were carefully constructed by his imagination.  The assembled objects in each portrait were not random: each was related by characterization.<ref>Maiorino, Giancarlo. ''The Portrait of Eccentricity: Arcimboldo and the Mannerist Grotesque.''  The Pennsylvania State University Press, 1991. Print.</ref>  In the portrait now represented by several copies called ''The Librarian'', Arcimboldo used objects that signified the book culture at that time, such as the curtain that created individual study rooms in a library.  The animal tails, which became the beard of the portrait, were used as dusters.  By using everyday objects, the portraits were decoration and still-life paintings at the same time.<ref name=\"Elhard, K. C 2005\">Elhard, K. C. \"Reopening the Book on Arcimboldo\u2019s Librarian.\" ''Libraries & Culture'' 40.2 Spring 2005. 115\u2013127. ''Project MUSE''.</ref>  His works showed not only nature and human beings, but also how closely they were related.<ref name=KAREN>{{cite news|last=ROSENBERG|first=KAREN|title=Several Obsessions, United on the Canvas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/24/arts/design/24arcimboldo.html?_r=0|accessdate=30 December 2012|newspaper=NY Times|date=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAfter a portrait was released to the public, some scholars, who had a close relationship with the book culture at that time, argued that the portrait ridiculed their scholarship.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}  In fact, Arcimboldo criticized rich people's misbehavior and showed others what happened at that time through his art.  In ''The Librarian'', although the painting might have appeared ridiculous, it also contained a criticism of wealthy people who collected books only to own them, rather than to read them.<ref name=\"Elhard, K. C 2005\"/>\n\n[[Art]] critics debate whether his paintings were whimsical or the product of a deranged [[mind]].<ref name=\"Souren\">{{cite news|last=Melikian|first=Souren|title=Giuseppe Arcimboldo's hallucinations: Fantasy or insanity?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/05/arts/05iht-melik6.1.7766101.html?_r=0|accessdate=30 December 2012|newspaper=NY Times|date=October 5, 2007}}</ref> A majority of scholars hold to the view, however, that given the Renaissance fascination with riddles, puzzles, and the bizarre (see, for example, the grotesque heads of [[Leonardo da Vinci]]), Arcimboldo, far from being mentally imbalanced, catered to the taste of his times.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nArcimboldo died in [[Milan]], where he had retired after leaving the Prague service.  It was during this last phase of his career that he produced the composite portrait of Rudolph II (see above), as well as his self-portrait as the Four Seasons.  His Italian contemporaries honored him with poetry and manuscripts celebrating his illustrious career.\n\nWhen the [[Swedish Empire|Swedish]] army invaded [[Prague]] in 1648, during the [[Thirty Years' War]], many of Arcimboldo's paintings were taken from [[Rudolf II]]'s collection.\n\nHis works can be found in Vienna's [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] and the [[Ambras Castle|Habsburg Schloss Ambras]] in [[Innsbruck]]; the [[Louvre]] in Paris; as well as in numerous museums in Sweden. In Italy, his work is in [[Cremona]], [[Brescia]], and the [[Uffizi Gallery]] in [[Florence]]. The [[Wadsworth Atheneum]] in [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], [[Connecticut]]; the [[Denver Art Museum]] in [[Denver, Colorado]]; the Menil Foundation in [[Houston]], [[Texas]]; the Candie Museum in [[Guernsey]] and the [[Real Academia de Bellas Artes de San Fernando]] in [[Madrid]] also own [[painting]]s by Arcimboldo.\n\nHe is known as a 16th-century [[Mannerist]].  A transitional period from 1520 to 1590, Mannerism adopted some artistic elements from the High Renaissance and influenced other elements in the Baroque period.  A Mannerist tended to show close relationships between human and nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsconnected.org/resource/93691/the-mannerist-style-and-the-lamentation |title=The Mannerist Style and the Lamentation |publisher=Artsconnected.org |date=2009-03-10 |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref> Arcimboldo also tried to show his appreciation of nature through his portraits.  In ''The Spring'', the human portrait was composed of only various spring flowers and plants.  From the hat to the neck, every part of the portrait, even the lips and nose, was composed of flowers, while the body was composed of plants.  On the other hand, in ''The Winter'', the human was composed mostly of roots of trees.  Some leaves from evergreen trees and the branches of other trees became hair, while a straw mat became the costume of the human portrait.\n\n==Legacy==\n\nIn 1976, the Spanish sculptor [[Miguel Berrocal]] created the original bronze sculpture interlocking in 20 elements titled ''Opus 144 ARCIMBOLDO BIG'' as a homage to the Italian painter. This work was followed by the limited-edition sculpture in 1000 copies titled ''Opus 167 OMAGGIO AD ARCIMBOLDO (HOMAGE TO ARCIMBOLDO)'' of 1976\u20131979 consisting of 30 interlocking elements.\n\nThe works of Arcimboldo, especially his multiple [[image]]s and visual puns, were rediscovered in the early 20th century by [[Surrealist]] artists such as [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. The exhibition entitled \"The Arcimboldo Effect: Transformations of the face from the 16th to the 20th Century\u201d at the [[Palazzo Grassi]] in [[Venice]] (1987) includes numerous 'double meaning' paintings. Arcimboldo's influence can also be seen in the work of [[Shigeo Fukuda]], [[Istv\u00e1n Orosz]], [[Octavio Ocampo]], [[Vic Muniz]], and Sandro del Prete, as well as the films of [[Jan \u0160vankmajer]].<ref>[Literature:''The Arcimboldo Effect: Transformations of the face from the 16th to the 20th Century''. Abbeville Press, New York, 1st Edition (September 1987). {{ISBN|0896597695}}. {{ISBN|978-0896597693}}.]</ref>\n\nArcimboldo's works are used by some psychologists and neuroscientists to determine the presence of [[lesions]] in the hemispheres of the brain that recognize [[Global precedence|global and local]] images and objects.\n\n==Art heritage, estimates== \n===Heritage===\n\n[[File:Print, Puzzle Picture of Napoleon, 1813 (CH 18553609).jpg|thumb|A 1813 Puzzle Picture of Napoleon, in the same style like Giuseppe Arcimboldo, hand-colored etching, in the [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum]] (New York City)]]\n\nGiuseppe Arcimboldo did not leave written certificates on himself or his artwork. After the deaths of Arcimboldo and his patron\u2014the emperor Rudolph II\u2014the heritage of the artist was quickly forgotten, and many of his works were lost. They were not mentioned in the literature of the 17th and 18th centuries. Only in 1885 did the art critic K. Kasati publish the monograph \"Giuseppe Arcimboldi, Milan Artist\" in which the main attention was given to Arcimboldi's role as a portraitist.<ref name=\"Werner Kriegeskorte 2000 p. 30\">Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). Arcimboldo. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. p. 30. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref>\n\nWith the advent of [[surrealism]] its theorists paid attention to the formal work of Arcimboldo, and in the first half of the 20th century many articles were devoted to his heritage. Gustav Hocke [de] drew parallels between Arcimboldo, [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]], and [[Max Ernst]]'s works. A volume monograph of B. Geyger and the book by F. Legrand and F. Xu were published in 1954.\n\nSince 1978 T. DaCosta Kaufmann was engaged in Arcimboldo's heritage, and wrote of the artist defending his dissertation \"Variations on an imperial subject\". His volume work, published in 2009, summed up the attitude of modern art critics towards Arcimboldo. An article published in 1980 by [[Roland Barthes]] was devoted to Arcimboldo's works.<ref name=\"Werner Kriegeskorte 2000 p. 30\"/>\n\nArchimboldo's relation with surrealism was emphasized at landmark exhibitions in New York (\"Fantastic art, [[dada]], [[surrealism]]\", 1937) and in Venice (\"Arcimboldo's Effect: Evolution of the person in painting from the XVI century\", Palazzo Grassi, 1987) where Arcimboldo's allegories were presented.{{sfn|Ferino-Pagden|2007|p=15}} The largest encyclopedic exhibition of Arcimboldo's heritage, where about 150 of his works were presented, including graphics, was held in Vienna in 2008. In spite of the fact that very few works of Arcimboldo are available in the art market, their auction cost is in the range of five to 10 million dollars. Experts note that it is very modest for an artist at such a level of popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/17/arts/design/17vogel.html?_r=0|title=Arcimboldo Work Bought in Time for Exhibition|author=Carol Vogel|work=The New York Times|date= September 16, 2010|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/09/16/AR2010091606901.html|title=Arcimboldo's 'Four Seasons' will join National Gallery of Art collection|author= Blake Gopnik|work=Washington Post|date=September 17, 2010|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref>\n\nArcimboldo's art heritage is badly identified, especially as it concerns his early works and pictures in traditional style. In total about 20 of his pictures remain, but many more have been lost, according to mentions of his contemporaries and documents of the era. His cycles ''Four Elements'' and ''Seasons'', which the artist repeated with little changes, are most known. Some of his paintings include ''[[The Librarian (painting)|The Librarian]]'', ''[[The Jurist (painting)|The Jurist]]'', ''The Cook'', ''Cupbearer'', and other pictures.<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. p. 16\u201420. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref> Arcimboldo's works are stored in the state museums and private collections of Italy (including [[Uffizi]] Gallery), France ([[Louvre]]), Austria, the Czech Republic, Sweden, and in the US.\n\n===Art interpretations===\nThe main object of modern art critics interpretation are the \"curious\" paintings of Arcimboldo whose works, according to V. Krigeskort, \"are absolutely unique\".<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. p. 20. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref> Attempts of interpretation begin with judgments of the cultural background and philosophy of the artist, however a consensus in this respect is not developed. B. Geyger, who for the first time raised these questions, relied mainly on judgments of contemporaries\u2014[[Giovanni Paolo Lomazzo|Lomazzo]], [[:it:Gregorio Comanini|Comanini]], and [[:it:Paolo Morigia|Morigia]], who used the terms \"scherzi, grilli, and capricci\" (respectively, \"jokes\", \"whims\", \"caprices\").{{sfn|Ferino-Pagden|2007|p=15}} Geyger's monograph is entitled: \"Comic pictures of Giuseppe Arcimboldo\". Geyger considered the works of the artist as inversion, when the ugliness seems beautiful, or, on the contrary, as the disgrace exceeding the beauty, entertaining the regal customer.<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. pp. 32\u201334. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref> A similar point of view was stated by [[Roland Barthes|Barthes]], but he reduced works of the artist to the theory of language, believing that fundamentals of Arcimboldo's art philosophy is linguistic, because without creating new signs he confused them by mixing and combining elements that then played a role in the innovation of language.<ref>Roland Barthes. Arcimboldo. p. 335</ref> \n\n<blockquote>Arcimboldo speaks double language, at the same time obvious and obfuscatory; he creates \"mumbling\" and \"gibberish\", but these inventions remain quite rational. Generally, the only whim (bizarrerie) which isn't afforded by Arcimboldo \u2013 he doesn't create language absolutely unclear \u2026 his art not madly.<ref>Roland Barthes. ''Arcimboldo''. p. 338</ref></blockquote>Arcimboldo's classification as [[Mannerism|mannerist]] also belongs to the 20th century. Its justification contains in Gustav Rehn Hok's work ''The world as a Labyrinth'', published in 1957. Arcimboldo was born in the late Renaissance, and his first works were done in a traditional Renaissance manner. In Hok's opinion, during the Renaissance era the artist had to be first of all the talented handicraftsman who skillfully imitated the nature, as the idea of fine art was based on its studying. [[Mannerism]] differed from the [[Renaissance]] art in attraction to \"not naturalistic abstraction\". It was a continuation of artistic innovation in the late Middle Ages\u2014art embodying ideas. According to G. Hok, in consciousness there is concetto\u2014the concept of a picture or a picture of the concept, an intellectual prototype. Arcimboldo, making a start from concetti, painted metaphorical and fantastic pictures, extremely typical for manneristic art.<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. pp. 56\u201358. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref> In ''[[On Ugliness]]'', which was published under [[Umberto Eco]]'s edition, Arcimboldo also admitted belonging to manneristic tradition for which \"...the preference for aspiration to strange, extravagant and shapeless over expressional fine\" is peculiar.<ref>''Storia della bruttezza'' (Bompiani, 2007 \u2013 English translation: ''On Ugliness'', 2007). p.169</ref>\n\nIn the work ''Arcimboldo and archimboldesk'', F. Legrand and F. Xu tried to reconstruct philosophical views of the artist. They came to a conclusion that the views represented a kind of [[Platonism|Platonic pantheism]]. The key to reconstruction of Arcimboldo's outlook seemed to them to be in the symbolism of court celebrations staged by the artist, and in his allegorical series. According to Plato's dialogues \"[[Timaeus (dialogue)|Timaeus]]\", an immemorial god created the Universe from chaos by a combination of four elements \u2013 fire, water, air and the earth, as defines all-encompassing unity.<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). Arcimboldo. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. pp. 58\u201360. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref>\nIn T. Dakosta Kauffman's works serious interpretation of heritage of Arcimboldo in the context of culture of the 16th century is carried out consistently. Kauffman in general was skeptical about attribution of works by Arcimboldo, and recognized as undoubted originals only four pictures, those with a signature of the artist. He based the interpretation on the text of the unpublished poem by J. Fonteo \"The picture ''Seasons'' and ''Four Elements'' of the imperial artist Giuseppe Arcimboldo\". According to Fonteo, the allegorical cycles of Arcimboldo transfer ideas of greatness of the emperor. The harmony in which fruits and animals are combined into images of the human head symbolizes harmony of the empire under the good board of the Habsburgs. Images of seasons and elements are always presented in profile, but thus ''Winter'' and ''Water'', ''Spring'' and ''Air'', ''Summer'' and ''Fire'', ''Fall'' and ''Earth'' are turned to each other. In each cycle symmetry is also observed: two heads look to the right, and two \u2014 to the left. Seasons alternate in an invariable order, symbolizing both constancy of the nature and eternity of board of the Habsburgs' house. The political symbolics also hints at it: at the image of ''Air'' there are Habsburg symbols \u2014 a peacock and an eagle and ''Fire'' is decorated with a chain of the Award of the Golden Fleece, a great master of which by tradition was a head of a reigning dynasty. However it is made of flints and shod steel. Guns also point to the aggressive beginning. The Habsburg symbolics is present in the picture ''Earth'', where the lion's skin designates a heraldic sign of Bohemia. Pearls and corals similar to cervine horns in ''Water'' hint at the same. {{sfn|Ferino-Pagden|2007|p=97\u2014101}}<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. p. 44. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nArcimboldo-style fruit people appear as characters in the films ''[[The Tale of Despereaux (film)|The Tale of Despereaux]]'' (2008) and ''[[Alice Through the Looking Glass (2016 film)|Alice Through the Looking Glass]]'' (2016), as well as in the [[Cosmic Osmo]] video game series.\n\nIn [[Harry Turtledove]]'s fantasy detective novel, ''[[The Case of the Toxic Spell Dump]]'', the [[alternate history]]'s version of Arcimboldo incorporated [[imp]]s \u2013 a common, everyday sight in that world \u2013 along with fruit, books, etc., into his iconic portraits.\n\nThe logo of the [[Arkangel Shakespeare]] audiobooks is a portrait of [[William Shakespeare]] made out of books, in the style of Arcimboldo's ''Librarian''.\n\nArcimboldo's painting ''Water'' was used as the cover of the album ''[[Masque (Kansas album)|Masque]]'' by the [[progressive rock]] band [[Kansas (band)|Kansas]], and was also shown on the cover of the 1977 Paladin edition of [[Thomas Szasz]]'s ''[[The Myth of Mental Illness]]''.<ref>See the 1977 Paladin edition of ''The Myth of Mental Illness''</ref>\n\nA detail from ''Flora'' was used on the cover of the 2009 album ''[[Bonfires on the Heath]]'' by [[The Clientele]].\n\nArcimboldo's surrealist imagination is visible also in fiction. The first and last sections of ''[[2666]]'', [[Roberto Bola\u00f1o]]'s last novel, concern a fictional German writer named [[Benno von Archimboldi|Archimboldi]], who takes his pseudonym from Arcimboldo.<ref>Bola\u00f1o, Roberto. ''2666''.  Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2008, pps. 729, 784.</ref>\n\nThe 1992 novelette ''The Coming of Vertumnus'' by [[Ian Watson (author)|Ian Watson]] counterpoints the innate surrealism of the eponymous work against a drug-induced altered mental state.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"168px\" heights=\"210px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldi 003.jpg|''[[Maximilian II, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor Maximilian II. of Austria]] and his wife [[Maria of Austria, Holy Roman Empress|Infanta Maria of Spain]] with their children'', ca. 1563, [[Ambras Castle]]\nImage:The Lawyer, possibly Ulrich Zasius, 1461-1536, humanist, jurist (Giuseppe Arcimboldo) - Nationalmuseum - 15897.tif|''[[The Jurist (painting)|The Jurist]]'', 1566, [[Nationalmuseum]], Sweden\nImage:Bibliotekarien konserverad - Skoklosters slott - 97136.tif|''[[The Librarian (painting)|The Librarian]]'', 1566, oil on canvas, [[Skokloster Castle]], Sweden\n\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - The Waiter - WGA0835.jpg|''The Waiter''\n<!-- File:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - Sketch for a Sleigh Shaped like a Basket of Flowers - WGA00877.jpg|''Sketch for a Sleigh Shaped like a Basket of Flowers'', 1585, [[Uffizi Gallery]] -->\n</gallery>\n\n==''Four Seasons''==\n<gallery widths=\"168\" heights=\"210\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - La Primavera - Google Art Project.jpg|''Spring''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.academiacolecciones.com/pinturas/inventario.php?id=0606|title=Arcimboldo, Giuseppe - La Primavera|last=Fernando|first=Real Academia de BBAA de San|website=Academia Colecciones|language=es|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>, 1563 [[Real Academia de Bellas Artes de San Fernando]], Madrid\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - Summer - Google Art Project.jpg|''Summer'', 1563, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]], Vienna\nFile:Arcimboldo, Giuseppe ~ Autumn, 1573, oil on canvas, Mus\u00e9e du Louvre, Paris.jpg|''Autumn'', 1573, Louvre Museum, Paris\nFile:Arcimboldo Winter 1563.jpg|''Winter'', 1563, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]], Vienna \n</gallery>\n\n==''Four elements''==\n<gallery widths=\"168px\" heights=\"210px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Arcimboldo Air (copy).jpg|''Air'', ca. 1566, (copy), private collection\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldo Fire Kunsthistorisches Museum.jpg|''Fire'', Oil on Wood, 1566, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] Vienna, Austria\nFile:Arcimboldo Earth.jpg|''Earth'', possibly 1566, private collection, Austria\nFile:Arcimboldowater.jpg|''Water'', 1566, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] Vienna, Austria\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hidden faces]]\n*[[The Librarian (painting)|''The Librarian'' (painting)]]\n*[[Hide-and-Seek (painting)|''Hide-and-Seek'' (painting)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Readings==\n* DaCosta Kaufmann, Thomas. ''Arcimboldo: Visual Jokes, Natural History, and Still-Life Painting''. \u2014 Chicago \u2014 London: University of Chicago Press, 2009. \u2014 313 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|9780226426860}}\n* Ferino-Pagden, Sylvia (ed). ''Arcimboldo: 1526\u20141593''. \u2014 Milan: Skira, 2007. \u2014 320 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-8861303799}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscatinline}}\n*[http://www.giuseppe-arcimboldo.org Giuseppe-Arcimboldo.org] The Complete works by Giuseppe Arcimboldo\n*{{IMJ-Collections|first= Giuseppe|last=Archimboldo|accessdate=September 2016}}\n*[http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/Arcimboldos-Feast-for-the-Eyes.html# \"Arcimboldo's Feast for the Eyes\"] ''[[Smithsonian Magazine]]''\n\n{{Giuseppe Arcimboldo}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arcimboldo, Giuseppe}}\n[[Category:1527 births]]\n[[Category:1593 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Milan]]\n[[Category:16th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:Italian male painters]]\n[[Category:Italian Mannerist painters]]\n[[Category:Italian portrait painters]]\n[[Category:Italian still life painters]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriates in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Austrian painters]]\n[[Category:Czech painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|16th-century Italian painter of the late Renaissance}}\n{{redirect|Arcimboldi|the cardinal|Giovanni Arcimboldi}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #EEDD82\n| name          = Giuseppe Arcimboldo\n| image         = Giuseppe Arcimboldo - Self Portrait - Google Art Project.jpg\n| imagesize     = 150px\n| caption       = ''Self-portrait'', now in [[National Gallery in Prague]], [[Google Art Project]]\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 1527 \n| birth_place   = [[Milan]], [[Duchy of Milan]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date|1593|7|11|df=y}} (aged 66\u201367)\n| death_place   = Milan, [[Duchy of Milan]]\n| nationality   = [[Italians|Italian]]\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      =\n| works         = ''[[The Librarian (painting)|The Librarian]]'', 1566<br>\n''[[Vertumnus (painting)|Vertumnus]]'', 1590\u20131591<br>\n''Flora'', ca. 1591\n| patrons       =\n| awards        =\n}}\n'''Giuseppe Arcimboldo''' ({{IPA-it|d\u0292u\u02c8z\u025bppe art\u0283im\u02c8b\u0254ldo|lang}}; also spelled ''Arcimboldi'') (1526 or 1527 \u2013 11 July 1593) was an [[List of Italian painters|Italian painter]] best known for creating imaginative portrait [[human head|head]]s made entirely of objects such as fruits, vegetables, flowers, fish and books.\n\nThese works form a distinct category from his other productions. He was a conventional [[court painter]] of portraits for three [[Holy Roman Emperor]]s in Vienna and Prague, also producing religious subjects and, among other things, a series of coloured drawings of exotic animals in the imperial [[menagerie]]. He specialized in grotesque symbolical compositions of fruits, animals, landscapes, or various inanimate objects arranged into human forms.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Oxford illustrated encyclopedia|date=1985-1993|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Judge, Harry George., Toyne, Anthony.|isbn=0-19-869129-7|location=Oxford [England]|pages=21|oclc=11814265}}</ref> The [[still-life]] portraits were clearly partly intended as whimsical curiosities to amuse the court, but critics have speculated as the degree of serious engagement with [[Renaissance Neo-Platonism]] or other intellectual currents that they have. \n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Vertumnus \u00e5rstidernas gud m\u00e5lad av Giuseppe Arcimboldo 1591 - Skoklosters slott - 91503.tiff|thumb|''[[Vertumnus (painting)|Vertumnus]]'', a portrait depicting [[Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor]] painted as [[Vertumnus]], the Roman God of the seasons, c. 1590\u20131. [[Skokloster Castle]], Sweden.]]\n[[File:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - Four Seasons in One Head - Google Art Project.jpg|thumbnail|''Four Seasons in One Head'', [[National Gallery of Art]], USA. ]]\nGiuseppe's father, Biagio Arcimboldo, was an artist of [[Milan]]. Like his father, Giuseppe Arcimboldo started his career as a designer for stained glass and frescoes at local cathedrals when he was 21 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giuseppe-arcimboldo.org/biography.html |title=Giuseppe Arcimboldo Biography |publisher=Giuseppe-arcimboldo.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref> \n\nIn 1562, he became court portraitist to [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand I]] at the [[Habsburg]] court in [[Vienna]], Austria and later, to [[Maximilian II, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian II]] and his son [[Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor|Rudolf II]] at the court in [[Prague]]. He was also the court decorator and costume designer. [[Augustus, Elector of Saxony]], who visited [[Vienna]] in 1570 and 1573, saw Arcimboldo's work and commissioned a copy of his ''The Four Seasons'' which incorporates his own monarchic [[symbol]]s.\n\nArcimboldo's conventional work, on traditional religious subjects, has fallen into oblivion, but his portraits of human heads made up of vegetables, plants, fruits, sea creatures and tree roots, were greatly admired by his contemporaries and remain a source of fascination today.\n\nAt a distance, his portraits looked like normal human portraits.  However, individual objects in each portrait were actually overlapped together to make various anatomical shapes of a human.  They were carefully constructed by his imagination.  The assembled objects in each portrait were not random: each was related by characterization.<ref>Maiorino, Giancarlo. ''The Portrait of Eccentricity: Arcimboldo and the Mannerist Grotesque.''  The Pennsylvania State University Press, 1991. Print.</ref>  In the portrait now represented by several copies called ''The Librarian'', Arcimboldo used objects that signified the book culture at that time, such as the curtain that created individual study rooms in a library.  The animal tails, which became the beard of the portrait, were used as dusters.  By using everyday objects, the portraits were decoration and still-life paintings at the same time.<ref name=\"Elhard, K. C 2005\">Elhard, K. C. \"Reopening the Book on Arcimboldo\u2019s Librarian.\" ''Libraries & Culture'' 40.2 Spring 2005. 115\u2013127. ''Project MUSE''.</ref>  His works showed not only nature and human beings, but also how closely they were related.<ref name=KAREN>{{cite news|last=ROSENBERG|first=KAREN|title=Several Obsessions, United on the Canvas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/24/arts/design/24arcimboldo.html?_r=0|accessdate=30 December 2012|newspaper=NY Times|date=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAfter a portrait was released to the public, some scholars, who had a close relationship with the book culture at that time, argued that the portrait ridiculed their scholarship.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}  In fact, Arcimboldo criticized rich people's misbehavior and showed others what happened at that time through his art.  In ''The Librarian'', although the painting might have appeared ridiculous, it also contained a criticism of wealthy people who collected books only to own them, rather than to read them.<ref name=\"Elhard, K. C 2005\"/>\n\n[[Art]] critics debate whether his paintings were whimsical or the product of a deranged [[mind]].<ref name=\"Souren\">{{cite news|last=Melikian|first=Souren|title=Giuseppe Arcimboldo's hallucinations: Fantasy or insanity?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/05/arts/05iht-melik6.1.7766101.html?_r=0|accessdate=30 December 2012|newspaper=NY Times|date=October 5, 2007}}</ref> A majority of scholars hold to the view, however, that given the Renaissance fascination with riddles, puzzles, and the bizarre (see, for example, the grotesque heads of [[Leonardo da Vinci]]), Arcimboldo, far from being mentally imbalanced, catered to the taste of his times.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nArcimboldo died in [[Milan]], where he had retired after leaving the Prague service.  It was during this last phase of his career that he produced the composite portrait of Rudolph II (see above), as well as his self-portrait as the Four Seasons.  His Italian contemporaries honored him with poetry and manuscripts celebrating his illustrious career.\n\nWhen the [[Swedish Empire|Swedish]] army invaded [[Prague]] in 1648, during the [[Thirty Years' War]], many of Arcimboldo's paintings were taken from [[Rudolf II]]'s collection.\n\nHis works can be found in Vienna's [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] and the [[Ambras Castle|Habsburg Schloss Ambras]] in [[Innsbruck]]; the [[Louvre]] in Paris; as well as in numerous museums in Sweden. In Italy, his work is in [[Cremona]], [[Brescia]], and the [[Uffizi Gallery]] in [[Florence]]. The [[Wadsworth Atheneum]] in [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], [[Connecticut]]; the [[Denver Art Museum]] in [[Denver, Colorado]]; the Menil Foundation in [[Houston]], [[Texas]]; the Candie Museum in [[Guernsey]] and the [[Real Academia de Bellas Artes de San Fernando]] in [[Madrid]] also own [[painting]]s by Arcimboldo.\n\nHe is known as a 16th-century [[Mannerist]].  A transitional period from 1520 to 1590, Mannerism adopted some artistic elements from the High Renaissance and influenced other elements in the Baroque period.  A Mannerist tended to show close relationships between human and nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsconnected.org/resource/93691/the-mannerist-style-and-the-lamentation |title=The Mannerist Style and the Lamentation |publisher=Artsconnected.org |date=2009-03-10 |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref> Arcimboldo also tried to show his appreciation of nature through his portraits.  In ''The Spring'', the human portrait was composed of only various spring flowers and plants.  From the hat to the neck, every part of the portrait, even the lips and nose, was composed of flowers, while the body was composed of plants.  On the other hand, in ''The Winter'', the human was composed mostly of roots of trees.  Some leaves from evergreen trees and the branches of other trees became hair, while a straw mat became the costume of the human portrait.\n\n==Legacy==\n\nIn 1976, the Spanish sculptor [[Miguel Berrocal]] created the original bronze sculpture interlocking in 20 elements titled ''Opus 144 ARCIMBOLDO BIG'' as a homage to the Italian painter. This work was followed by the limited-edition sculpture in 1000 copies titled ''Opus 167 OMAGGIO AD ARCIMBOLDO (HOMAGE TO ARCIMBOLDO)'' of 1976\u20131979 consisting of 30 interlocking elements.\n\nThe works of Arcimboldo, especially his multiple [[image]]s and visual puns, were rediscovered in the early 20th century by [[Surrealist]] artists such as [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. The exhibition entitled \"The Arcimboldo Effect: Transformations of the face from the 16th to the 20th Century\u201d at the [[Palazzo Grassi]] in [[Venice]] (1987) includes numerous 'double meaning' paintings. Arcimboldo's influence can also be seen in the work of [[Shigeo Fukuda]], [[Istv\u00e1n Orosz]], [[Octavio Ocampo]], [[Vic Muniz]], and Sandro del Prete, as well as the films of [[Jan \u0160vankmajer]].<ref>[Literature:''The Arcimboldo Effect: Transformations of the face from the 16th to the 20th Century''. Abbeville Press, New York, 1st Edition (September 1987). {{ISBN|0896597695}}. {{ISBN|978-0896597693}}.]</ref>\n\nArcimboldo's works are used by some psychologists and neuroscientists to determine the presence of [[lesions]] in the hemispheres of the brain that recognize [[Global precedence|global and local]] images and objects.\n\n==Art heritage, estimates== \n===Heritage===\n\n[[File:Print, Puzzle Picture of Napoleon, 1813 (CH 18553609).jpg|thumb|A 1813 Puzzle Picture of Napoleon, in the same style like Giuseppe Arcimboldo, hand-colored etching, in the [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum]] (New York City)]]\n\nGiuseppe Arcimboldo did not leave written certificates on himself or his artwork. After the deaths of Arcimboldo and his patron\u2014the emperor Rudolph II\u2014the heritage of the artist was quickly forgotten, and many of his works were lost. They were not mentioned in the literature of the 17th and 18th centuries. Only in 1885 did the art critic K. Kasati publish the monograph \"Giuseppe Arcimboldi, Milan Artist\" in which the main attention was given to Arcimboldi's role as a portraitist.<ref name=\"Werner Kriegeskorte 2000 p. 30\">Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). Arcimboldo. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. p. 30. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref>\n\nWith the advent of [[surrealism]] its theorists paid attention to the formal work of Arcimboldo, and in the first half of the 20th century many articles were devoted to his heritage. Gustav Hocke [de] drew parallels between Arcimboldo, [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]], and [[Max Ernst]]'s works. A volume monograph of B. Geyger and the book by F. Legrand and F. Xu were published in 1954.\n\nSince 1978 T. DaCosta Kaufmann was engaged in Arcimboldo's heritage, and wrote of the artist defending his dissertation \"Variations on an imperial subject\". His volume work, published in 2009, summed up the attitude of modern art critics towards Arcimboldo. An article published in 1980 by [[Roland Barthes]] was devoted to Arcimboldo's works.<ref name=\"Werner Kriegeskorte 2000 p. 30\"/>\n\nArchimboldo's relation with surrealism was emphasized at landmark exhibitions in New York (\"Fantastic art, [[dada]], [[surrealism]]\", 1937) and in Venice (\"Arcimboldo's Effect: Evolution of the person in painting from the XVI century\", Palazzo Grassi, 1987) where Arcimboldo's allegories were presented.{{sfn|Ferino-Pagden|2007|p=15}} The largest encyclopedic exhibition of Arcimboldo's heritage, where about 150 of his works were presented, including graphics, was held in Vienna in 2008. In spite of the fact that very few works of Arcimboldo are available in the art market, their auction cost is in the range of five to 10 million dollars. Experts note that it is very modest for an artist at such a level of popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/17/arts/design/17vogel.html?_r=0|title=Arcimboldo Work Bought in Time for Exhibition|author=Carol Vogel|work=The New York Times|date= September 16, 2010|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/09/16/AR2010091606901.html|title=Arcimboldo's 'Four Seasons' will join National Gallery of Art collection|author= Blake Gopnik|work=Washington Post|date=September 17, 2010|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref>\n\nArcimboldo's art heritage is badly identified, especially as it concerns his early works and pictures in traditional style. In total about 20 of his pictures remain, but many more have been lost, according to mentions of his contemporaries and documents of the era. His cycles ''Four Elements'' and ''Seasons'', which the artist repeated with little changes, are most known. Some of his paintings include ''[[The Librarian (painting)|The Librarian]]'', ''[[The Jurist (painting)|The Jurist]]'', ''The Cook'', ''Cupbearer'', and other pictures.<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. p. 16\u201420. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref> Arcimboldo's works are stored in the state museums and private collections of Italy (including [[Uffizi]] Gallery), France ([[Louvre]]), Austria, the Czech Republic, Sweden, and in the US.\n\n===Art interpretations===\nThe main object of modern art critics interpretation are the \"curious\" paintings of Arcimboldo whose works, according to V. Krigeskort, \"are absolutely unique\".<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. p. 20. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref> Attempts of interpretation begin with judgments of the cultural background and philosophy of the artist, however a consensus in this respect is not developed. B. Geyger, who for the first time raised these questions, relied mainly on judgments of contemporaries\u2014[[Giovanni Paolo Lomazzo|Lomazzo]], [[:it:Gregorio Comanini|Comanini]], and [[:it:Paolo Morigia|Morigia]], who used the terms \"scherzi, grilli, and capricci\" (respectively, \"jokes\", \"whims\", \"caprices\").{{sfn|Ferino-Pagden|2007|p=15}} Geyger's monograph is entitled: \"Comic pictures of Giuseppe Arcimboldo\". Geyger considered the works of the artist as inversion, when the ugliness seems beautiful, or, on the contrary, as the disgrace exceeding the beauty, entertaining the regal customer.<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. pp. 32\u201334. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref> A similar point of view was stated by [[Roland Barthes|Barthes]], but he reduced works of the artist to the theory of language, believing that fundamentals of Arcimboldo's art philosophy is linguistic, because without creating new signs he confused them by mixing and combining elements that then played a role in the innovation of language.<ref>Roland Barthes. Arcimboldo. p. 335</ref> \n\n<blockquote>Arcimboldo speaks double language, at the same time obvious and obfuscatory; he creates \"mumbling\" and \"gibberish\", but these inventions remain quite rational. Generally, the only whim (bizarrerie) which isn't afforded by Arcimboldo \u2013 he doesn't create language absolutely unclear \u2026 his art not madly.<ref>Roland Barthes. ''Arcimboldo''. p. 338</ref></blockquote>Arcimboldo's classification as [[Mannerism|mannerist]] also belongs to the 20th century. Its justification contains in Gustav Rehn Hok's work ''The world as a Labyrinth'', published in 1957. Arcimboldo was born in the late Renaissance, and his first works were done in a traditional Renaissance manner. In Hok's opinion, during the Renaissance era the artist had to be first of all the talented handicraftsman who skillfully imitated the nature, as the idea of fine art was based on its studying. [[Mannerism]] differed from the [[Renaissance]] art in attraction to \"not naturalistic abstraction\". It was a continuation of artistic innovation in the late Middle Ages\u2014art embodying ideas. According to G. Hok, in consciousness there is concetto\u2014the concept of a picture or a picture of the concept, an intellectual prototype. Arcimboldo, making a start from concetti, painted metaphorical and fantastic pictures, extremely typical for manneristic art.<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. pp. 56\u201358. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref> In ''[[On Ugliness]]'', which was published under [[Umberto Eco]]'s edition, Arcimboldo also admitted belonging to manneristic tradition for which \"...the preference for aspiration to strange, extravagant and shapeless over expressional fine\" is peculiar.<ref>''Storia della bruttezza'' (Bompiani, 2007 \u2013 English translation: ''On Ugliness'', 2007). p.169</ref>\n\nIn the work ''Arcimboldo and archimboldesk'', F. Legrand and F. Xu tried to reconstruct philosophical views of the artist. They came to a conclusion that the views represented a kind of [[Platonism|Platonic pantheism]]. The key to reconstruction of Arcimboldo's outlook seemed to them to be in the symbolism of court celebrations staged by the artist, and in his allegorical series. According to Plato's dialogues \"[[Timaeus (dialogue)|Timaeus]]\", an immemorial god created the Universe from chaos by a combination of four elements \u2013 fire, water, air and the earth, as defines all-encompassing unity.<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). Arcimboldo. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. pp. 58\u201360. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref>\nIn T. Dakosta Kauffman's works serious interpretation of heritage of Arcimboldo in the context of culture of the 16th century is carried out consistently. Kauffman in general was skeptical about attribution of works by Arcimboldo, and recognized as undoubted originals only four pictures, those with a signature of the artist. He based the interpretation on the text of the unpublished poem by J. Fonteo \"The picture ''Seasons'' and ''Four Elements'' of the imperial artist Giuseppe Arcimboldo\". According to Fonteo, the allegorical cycles of Arcimboldo transfer ideas of greatness of the emperor. The harmony in which fruits and animals are combined into images of the human head symbolizes harmony of the empire under the good board of the Habsburgs. Images of seasons and elements are always presented in profile, but thus ''Winter'' and ''Water'', ''Spring'' and ''Air'', ''Summer'' and ''Fire'', ''Fall'' and ''Earth'' are turned to each other. In each cycle symmetry is also observed: two heads look to the right, and two \u2014 to the left. Seasons alternate in an invariable order, symbolizing both constancy of the nature and eternity of board of the Habsburgs' house. The political symbolics also hints at it: at the image of ''Air'' there are Habsburg symbols \u2014 a peacock and an eagle and ''Fire'' is decorated with a chain of the Award of the Golden Fleece, a great master of which by tradition was a head of a reigning dynasty. However it is made of flints and shod steel. Guns also point to the aggressive beginning. The Habsburg symbolics is present in the picture ''Earth'', where the lion's skin designates a heraldic sign of Bohemia. Pearls and corals similar to cervine horns in ''Water'' hint at the same. {{sfn|Ferino-Pagden|2007|p=97\u2014101}}<ref>Werner Kriegeskorte (2000). ''Arcimboldo''. Ediz. Inglese. Taschen. p. 44. {{ISBN|978-3-8228-5993-3}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nArcimboldo-style fruit people appear as characters in the films ''[[The Tale of Despereaux (film)|The Tale of Despereaux]]'' (2008) and ''[[Alice Through the Looking Glass (2016 film)|Alice Through the Looking Glass]]'' (2016), as well as in the [[Cosmic Osmo]] video game series.\n\nIn [[Harry Turtledove]]'s fantasy detective novel, ''[[The Case of the Toxic Spell Dump]]'', the [[alternate history]]'s version of Arcimboldo incorporated [[imp]]s \u2013 a common, everyday sight in that world \u2013 along with fruit, books, etc., into his iconic portraits.\n\nThe logo of the [[Arkangel Shakespeare]] audiobooks is a portrait of [[William Shakespeare]] made out of books, in the style of Arcimboldo's ''Librarian''.\n\nArcimboldo's painting ''Water'' was used as the cover of the album ''[[Masque (Kansas album)|Masque]]'' by the [[progressive rock]] band [[Kansas (band)|Kansas]], and was also shown on the cover of the 1977 Paladin edition of [[Thomas Szasz]]'s ''[[The Myth of Mental Illness]]''.<ref>See the 1977 Paladin edition of ''The Myth of Mental Illness''</ref>\n\nA detail from ''Flora'' was used on the cover of the 2009 album ''[[Bonfires on the Heath]]'' by [[The Clientele]].\n\nArcimboldo's surrealist imagination is visible also in fiction. The first and last sections of ''[[2666]]'', [[Roberto Bola\u00f1o]]'s last novel, concern a fictional German writer named [[Benno von Archimboldi|Archimboldi]], who takes his pseudonym from Arcimboldo.<ref>Bola\u00f1o, Roberto. ''2666''.  Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2008, pps. 729, 784.</ref>\n\nThe 1992 novelette ''The Coming of Vertumnus'' by [[Ian Watson (author)|Ian Watson]] counterpoints the innate surrealism of the eponymous work against a drug-induced altered mental state.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"168px\" heights=\"210px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldi 003.jpg|''[[Maximilian II, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor Maximilian II. of Austria]] and his wife [[Maria of Austria, Holy Roman Empress|Infanta Maria of Spain]] with their children'', ca. 1563, [[Ambras Castle]]\nImage:The Lawyer, possibly Ulrich Zasius, 1461-1536, humanist, jurist (Giuseppe Arcimboldo) - Nationalmuseum - 15897.tif|''[[The Jurist (painting)|The Jurist]]'', 1566, [[Nationalmuseum]], Sweden\nImage:Bibliotekarien konserverad - Skoklosters slott - 97136.tif|''[[The Librarian (painting)|The Librarian]]'', 1566, oil on canvas, [[Skokloster Castle]], Sweden\n\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - The Waiter - WGA0835.jpg|''The Waiter''\n<!-- File:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - Sketch for a Sleigh Shaped like a Basket of Flowers - WGA00877.jpg|''Sketch for a Sleigh Shaped like a Basket of Flowers'', 1585, [[Uffizi Gallery]] -->\n</gallery>\n\n==''Four Seasons''==\n<gallery widths=\"168px\" heights=\"210px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - La Primavera - Google Art Project.jpg|''Spring'', 1563 [[Real Academia de Bellas Artes de San Fernando]], Madrid\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldo - Summer - Google Art Project.jpg|''Summer'', 1563, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]], Vienna\nImage:Arcimboldo,_Giuseppe_~_Autumn,_1573,_oil_on_canvas,_Mus\u00e9e_du_Louvre,_Paris.jpg|''Autumn'', 1573, Louvre Museum, Paris\nFile:Arcimboldo Winter 1563.jpg|''Winter'', 1563, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]], Vienna\n</gallery>\n\n==''Four elements''==\n<gallery widths=\"168px\" heights=\"210px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Arcimboldo Air (copy).jpg|''Air'', ca. 1566, (copy), private collection\nFile:Giuseppe Arcimboldo Fire Kunsthistorisches Museum.jpg|''Fire'', Oil on Wood, 1566, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] Vienna, Austria\nFile:Arcimboldo Earth.jpg|''Earth'', possibly 1566, private collection, Austria\nFile:Arcimboldowater.jpg|''Water'', 1566, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] Vienna, Austria\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hidden faces]]\n*[[The Librarian (painting)|''The Librarian'' (painting)]]\n*[[Hide-and-Seek (painting)|''Hide-and-Seek'' (painting)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Readings==\n* DaCosta Kaufmann, Thomas. ''Arcimboldo: Visual Jokes, Natural History, and Still-Life Painting''. \u2014 Chicago \u2014 London: University of Chicago Press, 2009. \u2014 313 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|9780226426860}}\n* Ferino-Pagden, Sylvia (ed). ''Arcimboldo: 1526\u20141593''. \u2014 Milan: Skira, 2007. \u2014 320 p. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-8861303799}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscatinline}}\n*[http://www.giuseppe-arcimboldo.org Giuseppe-Arcimboldo.org] The Complete works by Giuseppe Arcimboldo\n*{{IMJ-Collections|first= Giuseppe|last=Archimboldo|accessdate=September 2016}}\n*[http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/Arcimboldos-Feast-for-the-Eyes.html# \"Arcimboldo's Feast for the Eyes\"] ''[[Smithsonian Magazine]]''\n\n{{Giuseppe Arcimboldo}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arcimboldo, Giuseppe}}\n[[Category:1527 births]]\n[[Category:1593 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Milan]]\n[[Category:16th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:Italian male painters]]\n[[Category:Italian Mannerist painters]]\n[[Category:Italian portrait painters]]\n[[Category:Italian still life painters]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriates in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Austrian painters]]\n[[Category:Czech painters]]\n", "name_user": "FydelJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "adding bibliography on the information about the author's work located in Spain.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giuseppe_Arcimboldo"}
{"title_page": "Say So (Doja Cat song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Say So\n| cover      = Say So - Doja Cat.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = \n| artist     = [[Doja Cat]]\n| type       = single\n| album      = [[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]\n| released   = January 28, 2020\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   = 2019\n| genre      = <!-- Sourced in the \"Composition\" section. -->\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"Nylon\">{{cite web |last1=Wang |first1=Steffanee |title=Doja Cat's \"Say So\" Enters Billboard Hot 100, Thanks To TikTok |url=https://nylon.com/doja-cat-tiktok-say-so |website=[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]] |date=January 15, 2020 |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[pop-rap]]<ref name=\"The Oprah Magazine\">{{cite web |last1=Janes |first1=DeAnna |title=Who Is Doja Cat? All About the Artist Behind \"Say So\" |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a31123906/who-is-doja-cat/ |website=[[O, The Oprah Magazine|The Oprah Magazine]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[disco]]<ref name=\"The Oprah Magazine\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Sam |title=With Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love', Theatrical Pop Is Once Again Taking Over The Charts |url=https://junkee.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-pop/245988 |website=[[Junkee]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=March 10, 2020 |quote=[...] Doja Cat has nabbed a viral hit with disco tune 'Say So'.}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:58\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Kemosabe Records|Kemosabe]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Doja Cat|Amalaratna Zandile Dlamini]]|Lydia Asrat|[[Lukasz Gottwald]]|Yeti Beats}}\n| producer   = [[Dr. Luke|Tyson Trax]]\n| prev_title = [[Boss Bitch (Doja Cat song)|Boss Bitch]]\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| next_title = Like That\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|pok8H_KF1FA|\"Say So\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Say So'''\" is a song by American rapper and singer [[Doja Cat]], featured on her second studio album ''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' (2019). It was sent to American radio on January 28, 2020 as the album's fifth single. The song was written by Doja Cat, Lydia Asrat, Yeti Beats and [[Dr. Luke|Lukasz Gottwald]]. The song was produced by [[Dr. Luke]], under the pseudonym Tyson Trax. It gained popularity after a dance created by [[TikTok]] user Haley Sharpe went viral on the platform.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web |last1=Mamo |first1=Heran |title=Here Are the Lyrics to Doja Cat's 'Say So' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lyrics/8548599/doja-cat-say-so-lyrics |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=January 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"buzzfeed-dance\"/> The song has so far peaked at number nine on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Doja Cat's first top 10 single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9346375/weeknd-blinding-lights-number-one-hot-100|title=The Weeknd's 'Blinding Lights' Hits No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100, Doja Cat's 'Say So' Enters Top 10|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\"Say So\" was originally released as the fifth track on Doja Cat's second studio album ''Hot Pink''.<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/reviews/doja-cat-hot-pink|title=Doja Cat - Hot Pink - Clash Magazine|last=Bashford|first=Erin|date=November 8, 2019|work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Elle\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/music/a29737190/doja-cat-hot-pink-album-interview/|title=Doja Cat Just Wants To Make Rap Colorful|last1=Penrose|first1=Nerisha|website=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> During late 2019 and early 2020, the song gained popularity on the social media app [[TikTok]] due to several dance challenge videos that featured the song.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> Following this, the song was sent to United States [[contemporary hit radio]] as an official single from the album.<ref name =\"US Date\"/>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Say So\" has been described as a \"steamy, groovy\"<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> [[pop music|pop]],<ref name=\"Nylon\">{{cite web |last1=Wang |first1=Steffanee |title=Doja Cat's \"Say So\" Enters Billboard Hot 100, Thanks To TikTok |url=https://nylon.com/doja-cat-tiktok-say-so |website=[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]] |date=January 15, 2020 |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref> [[pop-rap]],<ref name=\"The Oprah Magazine\">{{cite web |last1=Janes |first1=DeAnna |title=Who Is Doja Cat? All About the Artist Behind \"Say So\" |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a31123906/who-is-doja-cat/ |website=[[O, The Oprah Magazine|The Oprah Magazine]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> and [[disco]]<ref name=\"The Oprah Magazine\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Sam |title=With Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love', Theatrical Pop Is Once Again Taking Over The Charts |url=https://junkee.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-pop/245988 |website=[[Junkee]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=March 10, 2020 |quote=[...] Doja Cat has nabbed a viral hit with disco tune 'Say So'.}}</ref> song. According to the sheet music of the song published at Musicnotes.com by [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]], \"Say So\" is composed in the key of [[D Major]] and follows a [[Tempo]] of 116 beats per minute.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0207459|title=Doja Cat \"Say So\" Sheet Music in D Major (transposable)|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Musicnotes.com|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The song additionally draws inspiration from 1970s [[funk]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.popbuzz.com/music/news/doja-cat-say-so-misheard-lyrics/|title=You've been singing Doja Cat\u2019s \"Say So\" lyrics wrong this whole time|author=Thompson, Sophie|website=PopBuzz|date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nIn her review for ''Hot Pink'', Lucy Shanker of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' deemed the song a \"traditional pop hit\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/11/album-review-doja-cat-hot-pink/|title=Doja Cat Scratches at Her Potential on the Mixed Hot Pink|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Shanker|first=Lucy|date=November 16, 2019|accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref> Nerisha Penrose of ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' wrote that the song \"offers a healthy dose of nostalgia as Doja's hushed, airy voice floats over a bed of iridescent synths and a funky bassline\".<ref name = \"Elle\"/> ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]'' wrote that the song is \"tied together with Doja's always perfect vocal performance\".<ref name = \"Clash\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nFollowing several viral dance challenge videos that featured the song, \"Say So\" became a [[sleeper hit]] on the record charts in a number of countries prior to being serviced as a single in late January. \n\nIn the United States, \"Say So\" initially entered the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] at number 19 on the chart issue dated January 4, 2020, where it moved up to number six the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/charts/bubbling-under-hot-100-singles/2020-01-04|title=Music: Billboard Bubbling Under Hot 100 Chart|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/charts/bubbling-under-hot-100-singles/2020-01-11|title=Music: Billboard Bubbling Under Hot 100 Chart|publisher=}}</ref> After two weeks, \"Say So\" earned Doja Cat her third [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] entry, and second from the parent album ''Hot Pink'', debuting at number 95 on the chart dated January 18, 2020. It jumped to number 77 in its second week on the chart, and gradually climbed up the chart. It subsequently started at number 33 on the [[Mainstream Top 40]], becoming her second single to chart on pop airplay following \"[[Juicy (Doja Cat song)|Juicy]]\"; it has since risen to a peak of number 11 on the chart.<ref name=\"Pop Songs\"/> Following the release of its music video, \"Say So\" ascended 18 positions to number 33 on the Hot 100 in its eighth week charting, while placing number 26 on Streaming Songs. It further reached number nine on the Hot 100, becoming her highest charting single so far.<ref name=\"Hot 100\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/streaming-songs|title=Music: Billboard Streaming Songs Chart|work=Billboard}}</ref> Consequently, it marked Doja Cat's first top 40 single in the country, surpassing the number 41 peak of \"Juicy\". It charted at number nine on the [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]].\n\nInternationally, \"Say So\" achieved top ten peaks in Australia, Belgium, Ireland, the Netherlands, New Zealand, and the United Kingdom. It also reached the top 40 including Greece, Scotland and Slovakia. \n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Say So\" entered the [[UK Singles Chart]] at number 83 on the chart issue dated January 9, 2020. It gradually ascended through the chart, cracking the top 40 at number 35 on February 13, 2020. It entered the top 20 at number 19 on February 28, 2020. The following week, it entered the top 10.\n\n==Live performances==\nThe song was performed by Doja on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'', on February 26, 2020. The performance features Doja Cat dressed in a baby pink bodysuit, along with two backup singers/dancers who execute disco-influenced choreography, which incorporated some of the dance moves from the viral TikTok routine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/doja-cat-delivers-sultry-say-so-performance-for-tonight-show-news.104862.html|title=Doja Cat Delivers Fun & Sultry \"Say So\" Performance For \"Tonight Show\"|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"Say So\" was released on February 27, 2020. It is \"[[disco]]-era\" themed set in late 1970s [[Los Angeles]], and filmed at the [[Sheats\u2013Goldstein Residence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3157849/doja-cat-say-so-video/|title=Doja Cat's 'Say So' Video Is A Shimmering, Disco-Era Thirst Trap|website=[[MTV]]|last=Roth|first=Madeline|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> In the video, directed by [[Hannah Lux Davis]], Doja appears in several different \"shimmery\" outfits and walks a tiger with a leash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/02/27/doja-cat-say-so-video/|title=Doja Cat Goes Disco in 'Say So' Video|website=Rap-Up|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> The video features Josu\u00e9 de La Vega as Doja's love interest and features cameo appearances from [[TikTok]] stars Dont\u00e8 Colley and Haley Sharpe, the latter of whom created the viral dance for the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nylon.com/doja-cat-say-so-video|title=Doja Cat Enlists Haley Sharpe And Dont\u00e9 Colley For \"Say So\" Video|website=Nylon|last=Halabian|first=Layla|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref> The dance itself, which made the song popular, was featured in the music video.<ref name=\"buzzfeed-dance\">{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/laurenstrapagiel/doja-cat-say-so-tiktok-dance-haley-sharpe|title=A TikTok Dance Has Made The Jump To An Actual Music Video|website=Buzzfeed|last=Strapagiel|first=Lauren|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n'''Jax Jones Midnight Snack Remix'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Say So (Jax Jones Midnight Remix) - Single on Apple Music |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/say-so-jax-jones-midnight-snack-remix/1499028545?i=1499028816 |website=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n#\"Say So\" ([[Jax Jones]] Midnight Snack Remix) \u2013 3:30\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (20